    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-01-14T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-01-14T11:00:00-05:00" n="291"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d291">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/7611: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-01-14T19:00:00+03:00"
                            >January 14, 1941—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 14—5:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>74. My 46, January 10, 6 p.m.<note n="22" xml:id="d291fn22">Not printed.</note>
                    In the course of a conversation this afternoon with the Rumanian Minister<note
                        n="23" xml:id="d291fn23">Grigore Gafencu.</note> he told me that the German
                        Ambassador<note n="24" xml:id="d291fn24">Friedrich Werner, Count von der
                        Schulenburg.</note> had informed him a day or two ago that he had received
                    word from the German Foreign Office that while substantial German troop
                    movements into Rumania had been taking place and would continue, they were being
                    made without any intention of offensive action in the Balkans and solely in
                    anticipation of a possible British move in that area.</p>
                <pb facs="0292" n="280" xml:id="pg_280"/>
                <p>The Minister also stated that the German Ambassador had told him that at the time
                    of Molotov’s visit to Berlin<note n="25" xml:id="d291fn25">Concerning Molotov’s
                        visit to Berlin November 12–14, 1940, see <ref target="frus1940v01#pg_573">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1940, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 573</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1940v01#pg_582">582</ref>.</note> he had been unwilling to
                    discuss the subject of the Straits with the German Government merely indicating
                    that the Soviet Government considered the Straits to be within its sphere of
                    influence.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
